President Donald Trump has announced his intent to nominate several individuals to key positions in his administration. John Jefferson Daigle of Louisiana is nominated to be the Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the United States to the Republic of Cabo Verde. Daigle is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and currently serves as the Designated Federal Official for the United States Advisory Commission on Public Diplomacy. Christopher Landau of Maryland is nominated to be the Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the United States to the United Mexican States. Landau is a constitutional and appellate attorney and has previously served as a law clerk for United States Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia and Justice Clarence Thomas. Bridget A. Brink of Michigan is nominated to be the Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the United States to the Slovak Republic. Brink is a career member of the Senior Foreign Service and has served in various positions advancing U.S. policy in Europe and Eurasia. Matthew S. Klimow of Virginia is nominated to be the Ambassador Extraordinary and Plenipotentiary of the United States to Turkmenistan. Klimow is a career member of the Senior Executive Service and has served in various positions in the Department of State, as well as in NATO and the United States Army.